After examining the only S‐production  
  S → NT146 NT9  
we see that NT146 has exactly one terminal production  
  NT146 → 't57'  
so any string derived from S must begin with t57.  Since the given string begins with t56, it cannot be generated.

After attempting all ways to split t57 t35 t77 t34 into a derivation of S → NT146 NT9, one finds that

• To get the first two terminals t57 t35 from NT146, use NT146 → NT188 NT169 with NT188 → 't57', NT169 → 't35'.  
• That leaves t77 t34 to be produced by NT9 → NT58 NT157.  
  – NT58 can produce exactly 't77' (matching the first of those), but NT157 always produces two terminals (it expands to NT8 NT119, each generating at least one terminal), so it cannot exactly yield the single remaining 't34'.

No other splitting works. Therefore the grammar does not generate the string.
